display="inline"><![CDATA[f , g \colon  \mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}Bx]]></fr:tex> be two dependent functions. A <fr:em><fr:strong>homotopy</fr:strong></fr:em> from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[g]]></fr:tex>, writing <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H\colon  f \sim  g]]></fr:tex> is given by a dependent function <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H\colon  \mathchoice {\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\textstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}{\scriptscriptstyle \prod _{  \mathopen {}\left \lparen x:A\right \rparen \mathclose {} }}fx=gx]]></fr:tex>. We shall write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[1_{f}\colon  f \sim  f]]></fr:tex> for the <fr:em><fr:strong>identity homotopy</fr:strong></fr:em> on <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> defined by <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[1_{f}x:\equiv  \mathsf {refl}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
